Leake  .","North German: habitational name from a place so named in Schleswig-Holstein.","North German: possibly also an altered form of   Lech  ."]},{"name":"Lechowicz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Leszek, Stanislawa, Wieslaw.","Polish: patronymic from the personal name   Lech  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Lech was born about 1172, in Castleford, Yorkshire, England as the son of Henricus de Leke , of Leche. He had at least 1 son with Joanna Pip. He died about 1196, in his hometown, at the age of 26."},"et":{"about 1172–about 1196":"umbes 1172–umbes 1196","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1172–1196":"1172–1196","1177–Male":"1177–Surnud","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1144–Male":"1144–Surnud","about 1172":"umbes 1172","1144":"1144","1177":"1177","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1196":"1196","1172":"1172","about 1196":"umbes 1196","1170":"1170","Castleford, Yorkshire, England":"Castleford, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1172–about 1196":"noin 1172–noin 1196","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1172–1196":"1172–1196","1177–Male":"1177–Kuollut","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1144–Male":"1144–Kuollut","about 1172":"noin 1172","1144":"1144","1177